                </span><br>
                <span class="process-list">
                    <i class="fas fa-plus"></i>
                    <strong>Feedback.</strong>
                    The tutors are great at getting involved in the students' projects and provides great feedback to
                    every step along the way.
                </span><br>
                <span class="process-list">
                    <i class="fas fa-plus"></i>
                    <strong>Pushes Learning.</strong>
                    Although I feel the course is spread to thin, which results in a feeling of having to much to do
                    , I still feel that the amount of work pushes us to learn a lot in a short amount of time, which
                    is very good.
                </span><br>
                <span class="process-list">
                    <i class="fas fa-plus"></i>
                    <strong>Easygoing.</strong>
                    It is easy to get in touch with the staff and just get to know them better. It makes for a very
                    comfortable learning situation where you're able to get to know your tutors and have a chat.
                </span><br>
                <span class="process-list">
                    <i class="fas fa-plus"></i>
                    <strong>Portfolio.</strong>
                    I like that we are encouraged to start working on a portfolio at a early stage in our degree. This
                    shows a focus towards helping the students get a job and not just teach how to a better academic.
                </span><br>
            </p>

            <h3>Cons</h3>
            <p>
                <span class="process-list">
                    <i class="fas fa-minus"></i>
                    <strong>Spread to thin.</strong>
                    The course have spread itself to thin when it comes to assignments. There are to many areas to focus
                    on at the same time and as a result of this I never felt proud of any assessments I turned in, as they
                    had to be rushed in order to jump into the next assignment. Moreover, based on basic UX psychology,
                    human beings are capable of focusing on 7 [+-2] things at the time. This subject alone has journals,
                    a major project, portfolio, and workshops that all have to be tackled differently in addition to
                    three other subjects who does the same, and thus quickly add up to the 7 [+-2] quota.
                </span><br>
                <span class="process-list">
                    <i class="fas fa-minus"></i>
                    <strong>Macro perspective.</strong>
                    As a result of a tightly packed course with three major project deliveries with pitches, one design
                    exploration with presentation, weekly journals, and a big portfolio at the end, I never had time to
                    take a step back and look at the bigger picture and plan ahead. For me this meant that I did not get
                    to plan out and establish a design/ working process for the current assessment, as I had to get
                    started writing if I wanted to see a ready product.
                </span><br>
                <span class="process-list">
                    <i class="fas fa-minus"></i>
                    <strong>Teach what you expect.</strong>
                    I feel there is a gap between what the course expects and what the course teaches. E.g., the design
                    exploration expected us to know how to digitally design a poster, but at this point in time we
                    had never touched on how to design a poster or the principles behind design. For the journals and
                    portfolio, it is expected that we analyse our design process, but the reality is that we have not
                    been taught a design process, and are expected to just come up with one along the way.
                </span><br>
                <span class="process-list">
                    <i class="fas fa-minus"></i>
                    <strong>Write everything twice.</strong>
                    Working on both the journals and the portfolio felt more like repetitive work than engaging and
                    rewarding, as they are but a copy of each other. Although the idea is to have quality in the
                    portfolio and quantity in the journal, you can't really write a journal without explaining somewhat
                    in depth, and you can't go much more in depth when writing the portfolio as there is not much more
                    to be said when I haven't had the opportunity to actually create a working process to analyse.
                </span><br>
            </p>
            <h3>Suggestions</h3>
            <p>
                <span class="process-list">
                    <i class="fas fa-exclamation"></i>
                    <strong>Combine Assignments.</strong>
                    Include the journals in the major project assessments as documentation or double down on the
                    portfolio and get rid of the journals. This would ensure the same amount of work, equal results, but
                    less things to keep track of and less repetitive work.
                </span><br>
                <span class="process-list">
                    <i class="fas fa-exclamation"></i>
                    <strong>Design Process.</strong>
                    If you wish to have students analyse their design process, include a design process delivery early on
                    so that students are forced to think through this at an early stage instead of having it as an after
                    thought in between all other assignments across all subjects.
                </span><br>
                <span class="process-list">
                    <i class="fas fa-exclamation"></i>
                    <strong>Workshop Lessons.</strong>
                    Lessons on Illustrator, Photoshop and InDesign should be front-loaded as the design exploration is
                    the first assignment to come up, and some people, myself included, have no clue what they are doing
                    in terms of design and approach.
                </span><br>
            </p>
        </div>
